# Rust Doesn't Have a Garbage Collector

This is a common misconception worth clarifying directly. **Rust has no garbage collector** — this is actually one of its defining features and primary design goals.

---

## How Rust Manages Memory (Without a GC)

Rust uses a compile-time ownership system to manage memory deterministically.

### The Three Rules of Ownership

```rust
// Rule 1: Each value has exactly one owner
let s1 = String::from("hello");

// Rule 2: When the owner goes out of scope, the value is dropped
{
    let s2 = String::from("world");
} // s2 is freed HERE, automatically, no GC needed

// Rule 3: Ownership can be moved or borrowed, not duplicated
let s3 = String::from("hello");
let s4 = s3;         // ownership MOVED to s4
// println!("{}", s3); // COMPILE ERROR - s3 no longer valid
```

### Borrowing and Lifetimes

```rust
// Immutable borrow - many readers allowed
fn print_length(s: &String) {  // borrows, doesn't own
    println!("{}", s.len());
}  // borrow ends here, original owner unaffected

// Mutable borrow - only ONE writer allowed at a time
fn append_world(s: &mut String) {
    s.push_str(", world");
}

fn main() {
    let mut my_string = String::from("hello");

    let r1 = &my_string;
    let r2 = &my_string;  // fine - multiple immutable borrows
    println!("{} {}", r1, r2);
    // r1 and r2 no longer used after this point

    let r3 = &mut my_string;  // fine - previous borrows are done
    r3.push_str("!");
}
```

